Great explanation, thank you for taking the time.

Well, as of right now I am using Degiro as a broker, which actually has a list select of free ETFs. So they don't charge fees on those. That's where I got my SP500 ( IE0031442068 ishares) and a MSCI China ( IE00B44T3H88  HSBC).

I know that the MSCI China might be hella risky, but that's why I wanted it, I am young, I want to take some risks while I can. And besides that's the smallest part of my portfolio right now (20%). TER is 0.6 , a little high but well can't learn if I don't try and make some mistakes. 

&amp;#x200B;

On the ETFs that are not on the list, Degiro charges me 2€+0.03% per order, so I was trying to find ETFs that suited my needs on the free list first. Unfortunately the only EU Healthcare on the list is the Lyxor EU 600 that I was asking about on the other thread.

&amp;#x200B;

I might spend some time doing the math to see what is the best way to approach an EU healthcare ETF like the one you suggested taking into account my brokers fees.

&amp;#x200B;

Thank you again for taking your time to do the write up

